# Swift conventions for Dub

The Apple shell consumes the Rust core via UniFFI. Swift code is the
chrome (toolbar, library browser, preferences); Metal-rendered views handle
the performance surface (waveforms, scopes).

## Always

- No implicit unwraps (`!`). Use `if let`, `guard let`, or `??`.
- All UI mutation goes through `MainActor`-isolated code. Annotate `@MainActor`
  explicitly when crossing actor boundaries.
- Never call into Swift from the audio render thread. The audio thread runs
  Rust code only. UniFFI bindings used by Swift are only called from non-RT
  threads (UI dispatch, worker queues).
- Snapshot test every view. `swift-snapshot-testing` is the tool. Failing
  snapshots block the PR until reviewer-accepted.

## Structure

- Views are small. Extract subviews when a body exceeds ~30 lines.
- View models are `@Observable` (Swift 5.9+) or `ObservableObject`. Pure logic
  has no UI dependency.
- One view per file. Same name as the type.

## Performance UI

- Use `MTKView` (subclassed) for waveforms and timecode scope. Not Canvas.
- Render loop polls Rust core state via lock-free atomic snapshots, never
  callbacks from the audio thread.
- Target 60 fps; 120 fps where ProMotion is available.

## Things to avoid

- Force-unwrapping optionals (`!`).
- `DispatchQueue.main.sync` from background — deadlock waiting to happen.
- `Thread.sleep` — never.
- Capturing `self` strongly in closures inside reactive code (use `[weak self]`).
